Abstract

The COVID-19 pandemic has been a transformative catalyst for digital payment adoption in India, with the Unified Payments Interface (UPI) emerging as a critical component of the nation's financial infrastructure. This study evaluates the impact of the pandemic on UPI transaction growth by employing a quasi-experimental research design that leverages time-series forecasting models. Utilizing monthly transaction data from the National Payments Corporation of India (NPCI) from April 2016 to March 2023, this research establishes a counterfactual scenario by training SARIMA, ARIMA, Prophet, and Holt-Winters models on pre-pandemic data (April 2016–February 2020). The forecasted transaction volumes and values are then compared against the actual data observed during the pandemic and post-pandemic periods (March 2020–March 2023). The primary objective is to quantify the deviation from the expected growth trajectory, thereby providing empirical evidence of a structural break in digital payment behavior. The findings indicate a statistically significant acceleration in UPI adoption that surpasses the pre-pandemic trend, with the SARIMA model demonstrating the best fit. This study contributes to the literature by moving beyond correlational analysis to offer a quantitative assessment of the pandemic's causal impact on financial technology adoption. The results have significant policy implications for financial inclusion, digital infrastructure development, and central banking strategies in a post-pandemic world.

